    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>CO, HCN, HCO+ and CS observations of the Carina Globule with angular resolution of 0.2"</prj:name>
        <prj:note>We aim at resolving, for the first time, the molecular emission and velocity pattern of small-scale sub-structures (0.2-1.0") observed inside an evaporating cometary gloubule (of size 4"x 9") located near the South Pillars in the Carina Nebula (d= 2.3 kpc). This object shows both features of an evaporating protoplanetary disk (proplyd) and an  evaporating globule (EGG) which suggests it may be going through a transitional phase described in the evolutionary scenario proposed by  Hester &amp; Desch (2005).   


ALMA in cycle 2 provides the necessary spatial/spectral resolution and sensitivity to resolve the emission inside the cocoon, giving insight on this object true nature. 
The selected frequency settings correspond to the lines J=3-2 of 12CO, HCN(4-3), HCO+(4-3) and CS (7-6) in band 7, already detected toward this object, but not resolved in single-dish observations. The observed lines have line-widths of 2-3 km/s and brightnesses of 3 to 33 K, and hence a spatial resolution of 0.2-0.3" and a sensitivity of 1K per pointing will guarantee the sucess of the proposed science goal. </prj:note>
