        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have chosen an angular resolution of 0.2", sufficient to resolve most of the interesting structures inside the cocoon of 9''. The observed line-widths for the CO(3-2) line in single dish observations is of the order of  3.2 km/s, and hence we adopt a spectral resolution of ~0.3 km/s (with a spectral averaging to avoid high data-rates). The observed single dish brightnesses for CO (3-2), HCO+(4-3) and HCN(4-3) in band 7 are 33.0, 5.0 and 3.3 K respectively. Adopting a sensitivity of 1K therefore yields SNRs of 33, 5 and 3, respectively. 

The CS(7-6) line was not observed previously, but in warm and dense gas it should be of comparable brightness to HCO+ and HCN and therefore we have included a baseband to detect it.


Other important lines could be also observed with these settings. In particular HCCCN, H13CN, HCO, and other complex molecular species.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
