    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Most low mass stars are born within transient OB associations, rather than in smaller dark cloud complexes, and there is now clear evidence that our own Solar System formed near massive stars. Hence, the study of the formation, properties, and evolution of Young Stellar Objects (YSOs) in massive star forming regions (SFRs) is more fundamental for understanding the formation of the Solar System than studies focussing on low-mass SFRs. Inside a HII region, YSOs are photo-evaporated by the strong UV radiation which limits their accretion reservoir prematurely and can truncate infall. Hester &amp; Desch (2005) proposed a well-ordered evolutionary sequence for YSOs as they, and their natal environment, are overrun by the passage of the ionization front.

Here we propose to observe one evaporating globule in the Carina Nebula that is likely in a transitional phase from EGG to proplyd. ALMA in cycle 2 provides the necessary spatial/spectral resolution (0.2-0.3") and sensitivity (4 mJy)to resolve, for the first time, the molecular emission and velocity pattern of sub-structures observed inside the globule, giving insight on its true nature. </prp:abstract>
    <prp:relatedProposals>Poster at the conference "The Universe explored by Herschel" (15-18th October 2013) on the results of Herschel/HIFI and PACS observations of the Carina evaporating globule. </prp:relatedProposals>
    <prp:previousProposals>A proposal was submitted in cycle 1 (project code 2012.1.00998.S) to observe the Carina globule and one of the proplyds in Orion. The proposal was entitled: "PROPLYDS: resolving the keplerian disk for the first time with ALMA".</prp:previousProposals>
